29535188-f241-4894-b19a-0f4679571131.2a869fc9-4492-426a-ad69-b553f6c647eb.description=Description\: This step creates a Data Guard Broker configuration by performing the following actions\: (1) Makes sure that the Data Guard Broker is installed on the primary database server and has not yet been configured. (2) Gets the DB_UNIQUE_NAME for the primary and each standby database. (3) Creates the Broker configuration. (4) Checks the status of the Broker configuration. Dependencies\: (1) Oracle database must be running on the primary database server. (2) The specified primary database is not read-only. Return Code\: 0 \= Step ran successfully 1 \= Step failed Inputs\: command - executes BuildDataGuardBrokerConfigurationv2.py Call Wrapper - Required\: Command that will execute the step as the OS administrative user (for example\: /opt/hp/dma/client/bin/jython.sh for UNIX targets). Connect Identifier - Required\: The connect identifier used to connect to the primary database. It is defined in the tnsnames.ora file. Make sure that the tnsnames.ora file on every database and instance that is part of the configuration contains an entry for this connect identifier. Data Guard Broker Config Name - Required\: For Configure Data Guard Broker task. The name that will be assigned to the Broker configuration that you are creating. Data Guard Standby Type - Required\: For Configure Data Guard Broker task. The type of standby databases that you are configuring. Valid values are Physical, Logical, or Snapshot (only Physical is currently implemented). Oracle Home - No description Oracle sys password - Required\: SYS Password for the primary and secondary databases. Primary DB Unique Name - No description Standby Connect Identifier - Required\: Comma-separated list of the connect strings used to connect to the standby databases. These are defined in the tnsnames.ora file. Make sure that the tnsnames.ora file on every database and instance that is part of the configuration contains an entry for these connect identifiers. Standby DB Unique Name - No description Standby Node Hostnames - Required\: Comma-separated list of up to 30 standby database server host names or IP addresses. If more than one IP address/hostname is entered, it indicates that the standby database is on RAC.  Purpose

This workflow enables you to deploy a Data Guard Broker configuration on Oracle 11.2 (or later) databases with Data Guard successfully installed and set up.


 Dependencies

This workflow requires Oracle Database Enterprise Edition version 11.2 (or later). It assumes that Oracle Data Guard has been provisioned. You can do this using the Provision Oracle Data Guard workflow.

This workflow also requires root and oracle user ID equivalence across all primary and standby database servers represented in the Data Guard configuration.

 Usage Instructions

Review the input parameters listed below, and create a deployment using values appropriate for your environment. This workflow is intended to run on the primary database server.

 Required Inputs

    Server Target - The desired target to run this flow against.
    Server Target Username - The user to login to the Server Target as.
    Server Target Password - The password to login as the Server Target Username.
    Download Source Host - The target host where the files needed for this flow can be downloaded from.
    Download Source Path - The path to where the files can be found on the Download Source Host.
    Connect Identifier - Required\: The connect identifier used to connect to the primary database. It is defined in the tnsnames.ora file. Make sure that the tnsnames.ora file on every database and instance that is part of the configuration contains an entry for this connect identifier.
    Data Guard Broker Config Name - Required\: The name that will be assigned to the Broker configuration that you are creating.
    Data Guard Standby Type - Required\: The type of standby databases that you are configuring. Valid values are Physical, Logical, or Snapshot (only Physical is currently implemented).
    Instance.name - No description
    Instance.Name - No description
    Oracle sys password - Required\: SYS Password for the primary and secondary databases.
    Oracle user name - Required\: Owner of the Oracle database software.
    Primary Node Hostnames - Required\: Comma-separated list of primary database server host names or IP addresses. If more than one IP address/hostname is entered, it indicates that the primary database is on RAC
    Server.Become Routine - No description
    Standby Connect Identifier - Required\: Comma-separated list of the connect strings used to connect to the standby databases. These are defined in the tnsnames.ora file. Make sure that the tnsnames.ora file on every database and instance that is part of the configuration contains an entry for these connect identifiers.
    Standby Node Hostnames - Required\: Comma-separated list of up to 30 standby database server host names or IP addresses. If more than one IP address/hostname is entered, it indicates that the standby database is on RAC.

 Optional Inputs

    Clean Code Base - Remove code base from target after execution (True || False).
    Clean JRE - Remove JRE from target after execution (True || False).
    Debug Level - Set level of output [(least) 1-5 (most)]

 Results Verification

The Console will indicate whether the workflow completed without errors. The Output tab  will indicate whether the specific Broker operation was successful. 

To further verify the results\:

 1. Set ORACLE_HOME and ORACLE_SID in the terminal to the targets.
 2. Log in to Data Guard\: dgmgrl sys/password
 3. Run this command\: show configuration
 


 Additional Documentation

Additional information about HP Database and Middleware Automation is available on HP Live Network\:

"http\://hpln.hp.com/group/database-and-middleware-automation"\:http\://hpln.hp.com/group/database-and-middleware-automation

To access the documentation, click the RESOURCES link and enter your HP Passport credentials.
